observations.recommendation:
Initiate the conduct of a complete physical inventory of the municipality’s properties by creating an Inventory Committee composed of a representative each from the Mayor’s Office, from the General Services Office (or the Municipal Treasurer’s Office) and a representative from each department to prepare the necessary procedures in the proper and orderly conduct of the physical count of the all the property, plant and equipment and inventories owned by the Municipality;

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all the properties recorded in the books and those not yet recorded but actually found in the LGU offices/premises and to prepare the corresponding inventory reports thereof; and reconcile them with the accounting records to come up with the correct account balances in the financial statement.

Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain stock, property and ledger cards, respectively to properly account the receipt and disposition of property and supplies.

Initiate measures designed to come up with a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) with the GSIS defining therein the agreed balance of payables to GSIS, if any, and the terms and conditions in the settlement thereof.  The following steps may help in facilitating reconciliation of records.

Secure detailed profile of payables per GSIS records;
Reconstruct old GSIS accounts, if necessary, and update records;
Reconstruct old personnel profile, if necessary, and update personnel profile;
Counter-check GSIS records with the reconstructed and updated accounting and personnel records of the LGU;
Negotiate with the GSIS for any differences that may be noted during counter-checking activity;
Enter into a formal agreement with the GSIS in the form of a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA); and
Appropriate fund for the settlement of any payables to the GSIS as agreed in the MOA.
